J. 10.1002/chem.201801064 Link to VoR: http://dx.doi.org/10.1002/chem.201801064 Yoshio Ando[a] and Keisuke Suzuki*[a]  HO Title(s), Initial(s), Surname(s) of Author(s) including Corresponding  Author(s)  Department  Institution  Address 1  O OH E-mail:   Title(s), Initial(s), Surname(s) of Author(s)  Department  Institution  Address 2  Supporting information for this article is given via a link at the end of  the document.((Please delete this text if not appropriate))  ((Insert Picture for Frontispiece here [18.0×18.0 cm]))  Abstract:  Photoredox  reactions  of  quinones  are  reviewed,  covering  classic  examples  as  well  as  recent  progress  focusing  attention on the utility in organic synthesis.  Quinones are widely distributed in nature as pigments in various  living  organisms  ranging  from  bacteria,  fungi  and  plants,  to  animals.[1] Reversible redox processes of quinone–hydroquinone  couples  play  a  key  role  in  metabolisms,  as  exemplified  by  phylloquinone (plants) and ubiquinone (animals) (Scheme 1).[2]  Scheme 1. Reversible redox process of quinones.

Irreversible transformations also occur in the vicinity of quinone– hydroquinone  scaffolds,  some  of  which  have  significant  biological  relevance.[3]  For  example,  the  biological  activity  of  nanaomycin  D,[4]  a  pyranonaphthoquinone  antibiotic,  centers  at  the Michael acceptor, generated by the quinone→hydroquinone  reduction  followed  by  expulsion  of  a  benzylic  oxygen  function,  which reacts with thio nucleophiles (Scheme 2).[3,5]  Scheme 2. Irreversible process of quinone derivative.  Photochemistry  also  provoke  quinones,[6]  as  Dr. Y. Ando, Prof. Dr. K. Suzuki  Department of Chemistry, Tokyo Institute of Technology  2-12-1 O-okayama, Meguro, Tokyo 152-8551 (Japan)  E-mail: ksuzuki@chem.titech.ac.jp  phylloquinone (vitamin K1) ubiquinone (coenzyme Q10) photorearrangement,[8]  conversions (Scheme 3).   Scheme 3. Photo-induced redox process of quinones.  During  our  recent  study  on  natural  product  synthesis,  we  came  across  an  interesting  photo-induced  oxy-cyclization,  i.e.,  an  intramolecular  redox  reaction  of  quinone  I  to  hydroquinone  II  (Scheme  4,  see  also  Schemes  18–20,  28  and  29).[9]  Note  that  the quinone is reduced, while the proximal C–H bond is oxidized.    Scheme 4. Intramolecular photoredox reaction of quinones.

Early  examples  of  such  a  photochemical  process  of  quinones  can be found in the 1960s’.[10] A general mechanistic framework  was  proposed  by  Baldwin,  involving  Norrish  type  II  hydrogen  to  give  abstraction  zwitterion  IV  and  cyclization  (Scheme  5).[11]  Importantly,  the  peripheral  radical  site  in  III  serves  as  an  electron  donor,  while  the semiquinone serves as an electron acceptor to become the  phenolate  in  IV.[12]  Our  recent  study  clarified  the  pivotal  role  of  the  electron-donating  substituents  (R,  R’),  which  electron transfer and also serve to stabilize carbocation in IV.[9,13]  Scheme 5. A general reaction scheme.  Although scattered examples of this type of photoreactions have  appeared,  little  have  been  exploited  in  organic  synthesis.  Thus,  this mini-review will focus on this topic with particular attention to  the  historical  background,  mechanistic  insight,  and  synthetic  implications. This article includes photoredox reactions of benzo-  and  naphthoquinones  (§2),  photooxidation  of  anthraquinones  (§3), and their utility in organic synthesis (§ 4).  2. Benzoquinones and naphthoquinones  In  1965,  Cameron  reported  on  photoredox  reactions  of  aminoquinones  (Scheme  6).[10a,b]  Upon  sunlight  irradiation,  benzoquinone 1 was rapidly converted to benzoxazoline 2. Also  cyclic  corresponding  benzoxazolines 6–8.  Scheme 6. Photoredox reactions of aminoquinones.  By contrast, the corresponding O-methyl derivative 11 remained  unchanged under sunlight, and prolonged UV irradiation caused  decomposition  (Scheme  7).  Thus,  the  peripheral  heteroatom  appeared to be critical; nitrogen is effective, but oxygen not.

Scheme 7. Attempted formation of methylene acetal (failed).  However, in 1966 Bruce reported that ether-type substrates with  weaker  C–H  bonds  underwent  the  photocyclization.[14]  For  example,  benzoquinone  13  with  an  O-benzyl  group  furnished  benzylidene  acetal  14  (Scheme  8a).  Isopropenyl  congener  15  reacted as well, giving benzofuran 17[15] via isomerization of the  primary product 16 (Scheme 8b). Quinone 18 with a butenyl side  sunlight→unchanged UV light→decomposed 6 n = 0: 73% 7 n = 1: 50% 8 n = 2: 54% chain gave dihydronaphthalene 21, presumably via biradicals 19  and 20 (Scheme 8c).  Scheme 8. Reactions of quinones with various side chains.  In  1970,  Bruce  reported  that  benzoquinones  with  a  formylalkyl  side chain, 22, 24, and 27, upon photoirradiation, gave lactones  23, 25, and 28 in low yields (Scheme 9).[16] In the case of 24 and  the  major  products  were  hydroquinones  26  and  29,  27,  suggesting competing intermolecular reactions.  Scheme 9. Substrates with a formylalkyl side chain.

reaction  of  In  1969,  Baldwin  the  photoredox  naphthoquinone  30  (Scheme  10a),[11]  related  to  Barton’s   proposal  on  the  biogenesis  of  methylene  acetals  in  natural  products.[17]  Upon  photoirradiation  of  30,  methylene  acetal  33  the  major  product  was  was  hydroquinone  34  having  an  acetoxymethyl  group.  As  noted  earlier,  this  report  was  the  first  that  proposed  the  currently  accepted  mechanism  featuring  an  electron  transfer  (31→ 32).  Another important observation was that non-bromo derivative 35  failed to give methylene acetal 36 (Scheme 10b). Entropic virtue  is present in 30  for facilitating the reaction, in that a buttressing  effect makes conformer B preferable, where the methyl group is  close  to  the  photoexcited  carbonyl  for  undergoing  hydrogen  abstraction.[18]  Scheme 10. Photoredox reactions of naphthoquinones.

In  1978,  Edwards  reported  the  photolysis  of  royleanone  methyl  ether (37) (Scheme 11).[19] Similar to the Baldwin’s report above,  irradiation  of  benzoquinone  37  in  acetic  anhydride  and  acetic  acid  gave  methylene  acetal  38,  albeit  in  low  yield.  Additional  products  were  quinone  39  with  an  acetoxymethyl  group  and  acetylated  hydroquinone  40,  which  could  be  regarded  as  a  redox  pair  of  disproportionation  products,  resulting  from  an  an  intermolecular  intermolecular  electron  transfer.  Interestingly,  when  benzene  was used as the solvent, Norrish–Yang cyclization proceeded to  give  oxetane  41,  along  with  demethylated  product  42  (royleanone).  The  oxy-cyclization  did  not  proceed,  which  might  indeed  produced,  although  be  related  to  Cameron’s  report  (see  Scheme  7).  These  solvent  effects  would  be  attributed  to  the  difference  of  polarity.  A  polar  solvent  (AcOH,  Ac2O)  accelerates  the  electron-transfer  step  to  form  zwitterion,  which  is  an  ionic  species,  but  a  non-polar  solvent (benzene) not.  Scheme  11.  Solvent  effect  in  the  photoreaction  of  royleanone  methyl ether (37).

In 2013, Gademann reported a related photoredox reaction in a  natural product synthesis.[20] At the final stage of the synthesis of  taiwaniaquinone  F  (43),  it  was  noted  that  strict  protection  from  light  was  necessary  during  workup/purification;  otherwise  facile  photoreaction  converted  43  to  taiwaniaquinol  A  (44)  with  a  methylene acetal (Scheme 12), suggesting that the latter is likely  to be produced by this non-enzymatic photoreaction in nature.  Scheme 12. Photoredox reaction of (–)-taiwaniaquinone F.  hν (mercury lamp) AcOH, Ac2O (–)-taiwaniaquinone F (43) royleanone methyl ether (37) (+)-taiwaniaquinol A (44) hν (mercury lamp) benzene Edwards  reported  the  photoirradiation  and  acetylation  of  royleanone (42) (Scheme 13a).[19] The product distribution of 45  (or 46), 48, and 49 suggests that the excited quinone reacted at  both  sides,  the  isopropyl  and  the  cyclohexyl  moieties.  The  structural  change  of  the  isopropyl  side  chain  was  explained  by  the intermediacy of spirocyclopropyl ketone V (Scheme 13b),[8,19]  suggesiting that many natural royleanone congeners differing in  the three-carbon side chain[21] may be photochemically produced.  The  formation  of  hydroquinone  47  implies  an  intermolecular  reaction.  Scheme  13.  Photoredox  reactions  of  royleanone  (42)  and  plausible mechanism of the side-chain modification. Simpler 1,2- and 1,4-naphthoquinone aldehydes  52 and 54 gave lactones 53 and 55 (Schemes 14b and c), and  interestingly 1,2-quinone 52 reacted much faster.  Scheme 14. Photoredox reaction of naphthoquinone aldehydes.  Kusumi reported that photoirradiation of tanshinone II (56) gave  a  including  9- hydroxytanshinone II (57) (Scheme 15).[23]  Scheme 15. Similar  photooxidiation  of  1,4-naphthoquinone  58  was  reported  by Krohn, giving ketone 59 (Scheme 16).[24] The mechanism will  be discussed in the next section.  Scheme 16. Photooxidation of 1,4-naphthoquinone. Scheme 17. Photoredox reaction of natural 1,4-naphthoquinone.

In 2017, we reported the photocyclization of 1,4-naphthoquinone  derivatives  (Scheme  18),[9]  which  was  discovered  during  the  synthetic study on the pluramycin-class antibiotics (vide infra).[26]   For example, quinone 62, under room light, gave spiroacetal 63  in  excellent  yield.  Naphthoquinones  64  and  66  having  benzylic  oxy-functions  underwent  photoredox  reaction  to  give  cyclic  products 65 and 67, respectively.   Scheme 18. Photoredox reaction of 1,4-naphthoquinone-1.  Naphthoquinones  68,  70,  and  72  with  six-  and  five-membered  carbocycles  gave  the  corresponding  spiroethers  69,  71,  and 73  (Scheme 19a and b). Note that substrates 68, 70, and 72 have  tertiarly  C–H  bonds.  In  contrast,  substrates  74  and  75  with  lesser  substitution  gave  no  photoredox  products,  but  an  intractable mixture (Scheme 19c). Also bearing quinone 76 with  an electron-withdrawing group (CN), only led to decomposition.   Scheme 19. Photoredox reaction of 1,4-naphthoquinone-2.

These substituent effect provided mechanistic insight. In relation  to the general mechanistic framework (Scheme 5), two important  factors are crucial, (1) the bond dissociation energy (BDE) of the  benzylic  C–H  bonds[27]  for  the  biradical  formation,  and  (2)  the  electron-donating  ability  of  the  substituents  associated  with  stability of the zwitterion.  The  photocyclization  proved  applicable  to  1,2-naphthoquinones  77  as  well  (Scheme  20).[28]  The  yields  were  slightly  lower  than  those  of  the  reactions  of  1,4-naphthoquinones,  primarily  due  to  the lability of 1,2-quinones and the derived products 78.   Scheme 20. Photoredox reaction of 1,2-naphthoquinones.  In 2017, Dougherty reported the use of a photoredox reaction for  chemical  biology.[29]  Upon  photoirradiation,  thio-substituted  benzoquinones  79  give  cyclized  products  82  and  S,  O-acetals  lactonization[30]  releases  various  83,  and  functional  molecules  (HOR)  (Scheme  21).  The  sulfide  moiety  serves  as  the  electron  donor  at  the  stage  of  electron  transfer.  Detailed  mechanistic  study  suggested  the  intermediacy  of  the  charge-transfer  state  80,  which  collapses  into  zwitterion  81  as  the immediate precursor to the products. Scheme  22  examplifies  an  interesting  photoredox  reaction  of  a  naphthoquinone.[31]  Menaquinone-1  (84),  a  vitamin  K  congener  with  an  isoprenyl  group,  underwent  photoredox  reaction  to  give  the  chromenol  89.  A  mechanism  was  proposed  with  intermediacy  of  intramolecular  exciplex  86.  Subsequent  1,4- proton transfer generates zwitterion 87, which tautomerizes to Z- 1,2-quinonemethide 88, and 6p-electrocyclization gives cyclized  product 89.  Scheme 22. Photoredox reaction of isoprenyl-naphthoquinone.  3. Photooxidation of Anthraquinones  Photoreactions  of  anthraquinones  have  also  been  reported,  although clear differences are present from the cases of benzo-  and  naphthoquinones.  Firstly,  all  photoreactions,  except  one  case,  were  performed  under  air  or  O2.  Secondly,  the  hydroquinones  are  easily  oxidized  by  O2  to  the  corresponding  anthraquinones. In all, the reactions result in the oxidation rather  than the redox reactions, and no oxycycles form.   In  1968,  Yates  reported  photooxidation  of  methylanthraquinone  90 to carboxylic acid 91 (Scheme 23).[32] The primarily generated  enol 95, a canonical form of biradical 94, is trapped by O2 to give  endoperoxide  96,  which  is  converted  into  formylanthraquinone  97, and subsequent reaction with O2 affords carboxylic acid 91.  Anthraquinone 92 results from photo-induced decarbonylation of  formylanthraquinone 97 (Norrish-type I reaction).[33]  Scheme 23. Photooxidation of anthraquinone.

The  pluramycins,  a  family  of  anthraquinone  derivatives  having  two  C-glycosides.[34]  In  1985,  Séquin  reported  the  photo- degradation of hedamycin (98) to give photohedamycin A (100),  possessing  a  glycal  at  the  C8  position.[35]  This  process  was  rationalized by photoreduction of quinone followed by an internal  hydrogen  abstraction  to  give  hydroquinone 99, and air oxidation gives 100 (Scheme 24).  hν (sunlight) air benzene 6 days Scheme 24. Photodegradation of hedamycin.

In  1988,  Blankespoor  reported  the  photo-demethylation  of  1- methoxyanthraquinone  101,  giving  phenol  105  (Scheme  25).[12]  The photoreactions were examined in the presence or absence  of  O2.[12a]  Mechanistically,  1,5-biradical  102,  formed  by  an  into  intramolecular  zwitterion  103  via  intramolecular  electron  transfer.[12b,c]  Capture  of  103  by  methanol  gives  hydroquinone  104  as  the  primary  product,  (1H  NMR  analysis).  When  104  was  exposed  to  air  during workup, the hydroquinone underwent air oxidation to the  anthraquinone,  and  the  labile  acetal  was  hydrolyzed.  A  radical  clock  study  identified  the  lifetime  of  1,5-biradical  102  to  be  1–2  ns,[12d]  which  is  approximately  one  order  of  magnitude  smaller  than  that  from  a  benzophenone  analogues.[36]  Thus,  102  is  rapidly  converted  to  zwitterion  103  via  electron  transfer.  An  additional kinetic study revealed the influence of the size of the  C2 substituent. For example, a substrate without the C2 methyl  group underwent demethylation much slower than 101, showing  again the importance of buttressing effect to place the O-methyl  group  close  to  the  photoexcited  carbonyl  for  the  1,6-hydrogen  abstraction[12b,c] (see also Baldwin’s example, Scheme 10).   Scheme 25. Photo-demethylation of anthraquinone.

Photooxidation  of  anthraquinone  106  was  reported  by  Krohn,  which  has  been  extensively  exploited  for  the  total  synthesis  of  the angucycline-class antibiotics (Scheme 26).[37] The process is  rationalized by the intermediacy of biradical 107 via the Norrish  type  1,5-hydrogen  abstraction,  which  is  trapped  by  oxygen  to  give endoperoxide 108. Elimination of water gives ketone 109.  Scheme 26. Krohn photooxidation.  4. Utility in Organic Synthesis  As described so far, many examples have been documented on  the  photoredox  (and  photooxidation)  reactions  of  quinones,  which,  however,  have  not  been  well  exploited  in  organic  synthesis.  This  section  will  describe two  examples  on the  utility  in natural product synthesis.  4.1. Krohn oxidation  As  mentioned  above,  the  photooxidation  of  anthraquinones  under  air  has  been  exploited  total  syntheses  of  the  II  (Scheme  27).[38]  This  angucycline-type  natural  products  photooxidation  proceeds  selectively  at  the  C1  position  with  various  functional  groups,  including  C-glycosyl  structures,[39]  in  tetrangomycin,[41,42]  the  MM4775,[41b,42,43]  B,[44]  urdamycinone  ochromycinone,[42,45] YM-181741,[42] and rubiginone B2.[42]  hv (sunlight) O2 CH2Cl2 7 h rabelomycin,[40]  E,[43]  Scheme 27. Photooxidation of angucyclines.

4.2. Stereospecific C–H functionalization  We  reported  the  stereospecific  C–H  functionalization  by  the  photoredox  reaction  of  naphthoquinones,  and  its  utility  was  demonstrated by the sucssessful total synthesis of (–)-spiroxin C,  a  marine  antibiotic  (Scheme  28).[46]  The  key  question  was  whether  or  not  the  stereogenicity  in  the  chiral,  non-racemic  naphthoquinone 109  is reflected in the photoredox product 110.  The  answer  was  affirmative,  as  a  stereospecific  reaction  proceeded  to  give  spiroether  110  as  a  single  isomer.  The  benzylic C–H bond in 109 was replaced by a C–O bond in 110  with retention of the configuration.  Scheme 28. Total synthesis of (–)-spiroxin C.  Scheme  29  shows  the  rationale.  Regardless  of  the  preferred  ground-state conformation, the initial hydrogen abstraction in the  excited  state  must  occur  within  a  conformation  A,  in  which  the  benzylic  hydrogen  atom  is  located  near  the  excited  carbonyl  group.  The  retentive  nature  of  the  process  is  explained  by  assuming  that  the  subsequent  events  proceed  rapidly  enough  relative  to  racemization:  1)  electron  transfer  from  biradical  B  to  generate  zwitterion C, and 2) cyclization of C to give oxacycle D. Although  the  central  chirality  is  lost  upon  hydrogen  abstraction,  the  stereochemical information is preserved within the axial chirality  of the intermediary species, radical B and cation C, thanks to a  scaffold  reminiscent  of  biaryl  compounds.  This  example  showcases a potential new way of enantiocontrolled synthesis.  Scheme 29. Rationale for stereospecific photoredox reaction.

The  historical  background  and  recent  progress  of  photoredox  reactions  of  quinones  have  been  discussed.  Recent  data  suggested  that  such  photoreactions  have  promising  potentials  as  enabling  tactics  for  complex  natural  product  synthesis.  For  the  future  progress,  the  substrate  scope  should  be  expanded,  and hopefully the intermolecular variant of C–H functionalization  would also be realized, thereby providing newer ways of organic  synthesis.   Yoshio Ando received his B.S. degree in  2002 and PhD. degree in 2007 in the  Department of Applied Chemistry, Tokyo  Institute of Technology guided by Prof.  Takashi Takahashi. He worked as a  postdoctoral fellow with Prof. Dale L. Boger,  The Scripps Research Institute (2007–2008).  In 2008, he was appointed as Assistant  Professor in the Department of Chemistry,  Tokyo Institute of Technology. His research  interests include the development of new  synthetic method and total synthesis of complex natural products.   Keisuke Suzuki obtained DSc. Degree in  1983 at the University of Tokyo guided by  Prof. Teruaki Mukaiyama. He was appointed  Research Associate to the late Prof. Gen-ichi  Tsuchihashi in Department of Chemistry,  Keio University (1983), and promoted to  Lecturer (1987), Associate Professor (1989),  and Professor (1994). He enjoyed a year as a  Visiting Professor at ETH Zürich (1990–1991)  with Prof. Dieter Seebach. In 1996, he moved  to Department of Chemistry, Tokyo Institute  of Technology. He has carried out extensive  research on organic synthesis with particular  emphasis on the development of new  strategies and tactics for total synthesis of  complex natural products.
